Indonesia Stocks: Indo Tambangraya, Bank Mandiri, Summarecon

-- B y   F e m i   A d i
-- 
2011-02-14T10:04:57Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-02-14/indonesia-stocks-indo-tambangraya-bank-mandiri-summarecon.html
Shares of the following companies
had unusual moves in Indonesian trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses, and prices are as of the 4 p.m. Jakarta-time close.  The  Jakarta Composite index  advanced 25 points, or 0.7
percent, to 3,416.77, rising for a second day.  Mining companies: Citigroup Inc. raised its 2011 nickel
estimate by 13 percent to $12.80 a pound, coking coal by 23
percent and thermal coal by 14 percent. For nickel, mine
projects using leaching technology will probably fail to reach
targets, “and nickel in pig supply will be unable to respond to
fill the supply gap,” Citigroup analyst Alan Heap wrote in a
report dated today.  PT Indo Tambangraya Megah (ITMG IJ), the Indonesian unit of  Thailand ’s largest coal mining company, Banpu Pcl, rose the most
in more than three weeks. Indo Tambangraya advanced 2.1 percent
to 45,200 rupiah. PT International Nickel  Indonesia  (INCO IJ),
the nation’s largest producer, gained 1 percent to 5,050 rupiah.  Banks: PT Bank Mandiri (BMRI IJ), Indonesia’s biggest bank
by assets, rose 1 percent to 5,600 rupiah. The state-owned
lender’s 2010 unaudited net income was 8.85 trillion rupiah, the
bank said in a report posted on the central bank’s website.  PT Bank Danamon Indonesia (BDMN IJ), controlled by
Singapore’s Temasek Holdings Pte and Deutsche Bank AG, was
unchanged at 6,150 rupiah. Bank Danamon’s 2010 unaudited net
income 2.88 trillion rupiah, it said in a report posted on Bank
Indonesia’s website.  PT Medco Energi Internasional (MEDC IJ), Indonesia’s
biggest listed oil company, rose 1 percent to 3,225 rupiah.
Crude oil futures slid as much as 0.1 percent to $85.48 a barrel
in after-hours trading in  New York  as of 4:34 p.m. Jakarta time.  PT Summarecon Agung (SMRA IJ), The Indonesian property
developer rose 5 percent to 920 rupiah. Summarecon will seek 720
billion rupiah of bank loans to finance this year’s capital
spending, including building two shopping malls near Jakarta,
Investor Daily Indonesia reported, citing President Director
Johanes Mardjuki.  To contact the reporter on this story:
